==========================================================================
SQUARE INTEGRATION
==========================================================================

Current Setup:
  - She already uses Square POS in-store (Square Terminal)
  - Full product catalog already exists in Square — items have serial
    numbers, descriptions, and can be searched/selected at the terminal
  - Inventory is already being tracked through Square
  - Photos: not currently attached to products in Square, but she takes
    photos for Instagram already. Just needs to upload them to the
    matching products in the Square dashboard (squareup.com → Items →
    select product → add image). May also be possible directly on the
    terminal via the Item Library.
  - Square Online: NOT yet activated — terminal shows "create site to
    access additional settings." One click to set up when ready, will
    pull from the existing product catalog.
  - All Square options sync inventory (in-store + online = one system)

How the sync works:
  - Website pulls directly from her Square catalog
  - When she adds a photo to a product in Square → shows on website
  - When she updates a price in Square → updates on website
  - When something sells at the till → disappears or shows "sold" online
  - One system, no double entry

Integration Options:
  - Option 1: Square Online — Square's own e-commerce page. Automatically
    reflects everything in her catalog (photos, prices, stock). When she
    adds a new product in Square, it appears on the site automatically.
    Less control over how it looks, but she can manage the shop herself
    without calling the developer.
  - Option 2: Square Web Payments SDK — fully custom cart/checkout on our
    site, Square handles payment processing. Most work, full design control.
  - Option 3: Square Buy Now Buttons — embed buy buttons on product
    listings. Existing products auto-update (price, stock, photos), BUT
    new products don't appear automatically — developer has to generate
    a new button and paste it into the HTML each time.
  - Option 4 (sweet spot?): Embed Square Online into our custom site.
    Square Online handles the shop page content (auto-updating from her
    catalog), and we wrap the rest of the site in our custom design.
    She manages products, we control the look.
  - Recommendation: Option 1 or 4 if she wants to manage the shop
    herself. Option 3 if she's fine with developer adding new listings.

Key question for owner:
  Does she want to add new products to the website herself without
  calling the developer? If yes → Square Online (Option 1 or 4).
  If she's fine with occasional dev help → Buy Now buttons (Option 3).

Workflow for adding products (with Square Online):
  1. She takes a photo of a product (already doing this for Instagram)
  2. Uploads it to the matching product in her Square dashboard
  3. It shows up on the website automatically — no code editing needed

Square Online Pricing (Canada):
  - Free plan: $0/month
    - Basic store, buy buttons, inventory sync with POS
    - Square branding on checkout, limited customization
  - Plus: $36/mo (annual)
    - Custom domain, no Square branding, more design control
  - Premium: $99/mo (annual)
    - Real-time shipping rates, lower fees, 24/7 support
  - Transaction fees: ~2.8% + $0.30 per online sale (vs 2.5% in-store)
  - Buy Now buttons: free on all plans — just paste HTML snippet into site
  - Start on free plan, upgrade later if needed

Open Questions:
  - Can we integrate Square Online directly into our custom site?
  - Or build our own cart and use Square just for payment processing?
  - Do we need a full e-commerce platform (Shopify, WooCommerce) instead?
  - Transaction fees for each option?
  - Canadian tax collection (GST) — how does that get handled?


