==========================================================================
ONGOING MAINTENANCE — WHO UPDATES WHAT?
==========================================================================

The Problem:
  Right now the site is static HTML (plain webpage files). Every time
  something needs to change — new product, new artist, price update,
  mark something sold — someone has to manually edit the HTML code and
  re-upload it to the server. That's fine for a launch, but not
  sustainable long-term if changes are frequent.

Options for handling updates:

  Option A: Developer does it (simplest, but creates dependency)
    - Owner sends updates (new artist, new product, etc.)
    - Developer edits the HTML files and uploads via cPanel
      (cPanel = the control panel for managing the web hosting server)
    - Pro: no new tech to build
    - Con: owner depends on developer for every change

  Option B: Square handles the shop, developer handles artists
    - Shop inventory managed through owner's existing Square dashboard
      — she already knows how to use it
    - She adds/removes products, updates prices in Square
    - Square keeps the online shop in sync automatically
    - Artist pages still need manual HTML edits by developer
    - Pro: shop runs itself, only artist changes need dev work
    - Con: artist pages still manual

  Option C: Build a CMS (Content Management System) — the real solution
    - CMS = a simple admin panel / website the owner logs into
    - She fills in a form (artist name, photo, bio) and it updates the
      live site automatically — no code editing needed
    - Could manage: artist profiles, shop inventory, contact info, hours
    - Pro: owner is fully independent
    - Con: big build — requires a backend (server-side code, database),
      not just HTML anymore. Significant development effort.

  Option D: Rebuild in WordPress
    - WordPress = a popular website platform with a built-in admin panel
    - BlackSun hosting supports it with one-click install
    - Owner manages content through WordPress dashboard (no code needed)
    - Pro: proven system, tons of plugins for shops/galleries
    - Con: means rebuilding the whole site in WordPress instead of
      custom HTML. Less design control unless you build a custom theme.

Recommendation:
  - For now: Option B — Square handles the shop, developer handles
    artist pages manually
  - Ask the owner: how often does the artist roster change? If it's a
    few times a year, manual updates are fine. If it's constant, she
    needs Option C or D.
  - Long-term: either build a CMS (Option C) or migrate to WordPress
    (Option D) so she's not dependent on a developer


