==========================================================================
GLOSSARY — WHAT THE ACRONYMS MEAN
==========================================================================

  HTML   — HyperText Markup Language. The code that makes up a webpage.
  CSS    — Cascading Style Sheets. Controls how the webpage looks
           (colors, fonts, layout).
  CMS    — Content Management System. A tool that lets non-technical
           people edit a website through a simple interface instead of
           editing code directly. WordPress is the most common example.
  cPanel — Control Panel. The dashboard for managing web hosting — file
           uploads, email accounts, databases, etc. Provided by BlackSun.
  FTP    — File Transfer Protocol. A way to upload/download files to/from
           a web server. Like drag-and-drop for websites.
  SFTP   — Secure File Transfer Protocol. Same as FTP but encrypted
           (more secure).
  SSH    — Secure Shell. A way to remotely access and control a server
           via command line (text commands).
  SSL    — Secure Sockets Layer. Encrypts the connection between a
           visitor's browser and the website. Makes the URL show "https"
           and the padlock icon. Required for taking payments online.
  SEO    — Search Engine Optimization. Making the site show up higher
           in Google search results.
  POS    — Point of Sale. The system used to process payments in-store
           (the till / cash register). She uses Square POS.
  API    — Application Programming Interface. A way for two systems to
           talk to each other. Example: our website talking to Square
           to process a payment.
  SDK    — Software Development Kit. A set of tools/code provided by a
           company (like Square) to help developers build integrations
           with their system.
  GST    — Goods and Services Tax. Canadian federal sales tax (5%).
  2FA    — Two-Factor Authentication. A security feature that requires
           a second verification step (like a code sent to your phone)
           when logging in.


